definition.value: This is an AE which is an itchy eruption of the skin.
This is an AE which may mimic diseases that present with annular configuration and the differential diagnosis is broad.
This is an AE which is an infectious disease caused by the cowpox virus.
This is an AE which is a large, complex, enveloped virus belonging to the poxvirus family.
This is an AE which is a slow-growing (16- to 20-hour generation time) aerobic bacterium and the causative agent of tuberculosis in cattle (known as bovine TB).
This is an AE which is flat, hyperpigmented birthmarks.
This is an AE which is clusters of concentrated melaninized cells which are most easily visible on people with a fair complexion.
This is an AE which is a small pigmented spot on the skin with a clearly defined edge, surrounded by normal-appearing skin.
This is an AE which is a skin condition characterized by excessively dry skin.
This is an AE which is a skin condition characterized by excessively dry skin.
This is an AE which is a discoloration of the human skin caused by a vascular anomaly (a capillary malformation in the skin).
This is an AE which is a condition in which hair is lost from some or all areas of the body.
This is an AE which is a condition characterized by a skin eruption on the trunk and proximal extremities.
This is an AE which is redness of the skin or mucous membranes, caused by hyperemia (increased blood flow) in superficial capillaries and it is epiglottic.
This is an AE which is a common type of conjunctival stromal degeneration in the eye.
This is an AE which is a medical condition which may result in blurred or no vision in the center of the visual field.
This is an AE which is a firmly attached white patch on a mucous membrane which is associated with increased risk of cancer.
This is an AE which is a form of radiation burn that affects living tissue, such as skin, that results from an overexposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation, usually from the Sun.
This is an AE which is blemishes on the skin associated with aging and exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
This is an AE which is a form of scleroderma that involves isolated patches of hardened skin on the face, hands, and feet, or anywhere else on the body, with no internal organ involvement.
This is an AE which is a microscopic exocrine gland in the skin that opens into a hair follicle to secrete an oily or waxy matter, called sebum, which lubricates the hair and skin of mammals.
This is an AE which is the (uncontrolled) death of cells in the (cerebral) cortex of the brain in a band-like pattern,with a relative preservation of cells immediately adjacent to the meninges.
This is an AE which is a rare neurodegenerative disease involving the cerebral cortex and the basal ganglia.
This is an AE which is one specific measure of bodily symmetry.

This is an AE which is feel discomfortable of a family of skin care treatments for the face, including steam, exfoliation (physical and chemical), extraction, creams, lotions, facial masks, peels, and massage.
This is an AE which is a rare neuromuscular disease characterized by irregular, involuntary muscle contractions (spasms) on one side (hemi-) of the face (-facial).
This is an AE which is sensitivity of a powder made by grinding raw grains, roots, beans, nuts, or seeds.
This is an AE which is a bacterial infection that involves the superficial skin.
This is an AE which is used for a heterogeneous group of diseases that share pustular skin characteristics.
This is an AE which is a chronic inflammatory and immune-mediated disease that affects the skin, nails, hair, and mucous membranes.
This is an AE which is highly inflammatory skin condition resulting in large fluid-filled blister-like areas - pustules and it is eosinophilic .

This is an AE which is an itchy rash with an unknown cause that is most common among individuals with HIV, though it can occur in HIV-negative individuals where it is known by the eponym Ofuji disease.
This is an AE which is a cutaneous condition characterized by deposits of excessive amounts of collagen which gives rise to a raised scar, but not to the degree observed with keloids.
This is an AE which refers to one of a group of skin disorders that are characterized primarily by their resemblance to psoriasis (red, scaly lesions), rather than by their underlying cause.
This is an AE which is a family of genetic skin disorders characterized by dry, thickened, scaly skin.
This is an AE which is a polymorphic, pruritic, papulovesicular dermatosis characterized histologically by acantholysis with or without dyskeratosis.
This is an AE which is a condition where purpura, which constitutes visible non-blanching hemorrhages, are raised and able to be touched or felt upon palpation.
This is an AE which implies that this nevus exists as a distinct and defined entity of potential detriment to its host.

This is an AE which is a type of telangiectasis (swollen blood vessels) found slightly beneath the skin surface, often containing a central red spot and deep reddish extensions (see Blood color) which radiate outwards like a spider's web or a spider's legs.
This is an AE which is a deep folliculitis on eyelid, infection of the hair follicle.
This is an AE which is a common type of contagious, superficial fungal infection of the groin region, which occurs predominantly but not exclusively in men and in hot-humid climates.

This is an AE which is a bacterial skin infection caused by Staphylococcus aureus that results in the formation of large blisters called bullae, usually in areas with skin folds like the armpit, groin, between the fingers or toes, beneath the breast, and between the buttocks. It accounts for 30% of cases of impetigo, the other 70% being non-bullous impetigo.
This is an AE which is a type of dermatitis that is characterized by itchy blisters on the palms of the hands and bottoms of the feet.

This is an AE which is a chronic recurrent pustular dermatosis (that is, a pustulosis or pustular psoriasis) localized on the palms and soles only, characterized histologically by intraepidermal pustules filled with neutrophils.
This is an AE which attributed to Heinrich Kbner, is the appearance of skin lesions on lines of trauma.
This is an AE which involves a neuropathic component is often of mild intensity.
This is an AE which is the formation of a type of scar which, depending on its maturity, is composed mainly of either type III (early) or type I (late) collagen.
This is an AE which is a cutaneous condition characterized by rough, yellow-brown keratotic, flat-topped papules.
This is an AE which is a deep folliculitis, infection of the hair follicle.
This is an AE which is largely dermatological conditions, which present clinically as cutaneous photosensitivity.
